<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-352-602  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 352 602.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  June 13 1989 v3 n23 p28(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Innovation still comes from individuals. (Editorial)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>Innovation still comes from individualsandM;From time to time as we report on the acquisitions, lawsuits and assortedmuscle tactics employed by the giants of the personal computer softwareindustry, we worry that the software business is headed for a futuremonopolized by megapublishers.andM;This scenario draws on the history of the U.S.andP;  automotive industry.andP;  Itsearly legion of innovative, enterprising companies were systematicallyswallowed up into a few conglomerates, each more concerned with capturingmarket share than with producing exciting new products.andM;But last month's Software Publishers Association meeting provided a reminderthat the best software ideas don't emerge from corporate committee rooms butfrom the imaginations of individuals or small teams of programmers workingindependently.andP;  The conference program may have been dominated by Microsoft,Lotus and Ashton-Tate, but the exciting new ideas invariably came from smallcompanies.andP;  It was appropriate that the big winner of the SPA awards, Tetris,was dreamed up by an amateur programmer working from his apartment in, of allplaces, the Soviet Union.andM;The giants may gobble up good ideas as they come along, but innovation, thelifeblood of theandM;business, will be generated by individuals for as far into the futureandM;as we can see.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>